            <div class="header">
                <h1>Guide to Plastic Types</h1>
                <p style="text-align: center;">Understanding different types of plastic is crucial for proper recycling. Each type has unique properties and recycling requirements. Learn about the seven main types of plastic below.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="plastic-grid" >
                <div class="plastic-card" style="justify-content: center; align-items: center;">
                    <div class="plastic-number">1</div>
                    <img class="plastic-logo" src="/image/plaslogo1.jpg" style="align-items: center; justify-content: center;" alt="PET plastic symbol">
                    <h2 class="plastic-title">PET (Polyethylene Terephthalate)</h2>
                    <p class="plastic-description">Commonly used in beverage bottles and food containers. Clear, strong, and lightweight. Highly recyclable and often turned into fibers for clothing or new containers.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="plastic-card">
                    <div class="plastic-number">2</div>
                    <img class="plastic-logo" src="/image/plaslogo2.png" alt="HDPE plastic symbol">
                    <h2 class="plastic-title">HDPE (High-Density Polyethylene)</h2>
                    <p class="plastic-description">Used in milk jugs, shampoo bottles, and cleaning products. Stiff plastic with good chemical resistance. Widely recycled into new containers, plastic lumber, and pipes.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="plastic-card">
                    <div class="plastic-number">3</div>
                    <img class="plastic-logo" src="/image/plaslogo3.jpg" alt="PVC plastic symbol">
                    <h2 class="plastic-title">PVC (Polyvinyl Chloride)</h2>
                    <p class="plastic-description">Found in plumbing pipes, window frames, and some food packaging. Durable and weather-resistant. Limited recycling options due to chemical composition.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="plastic-card">
                    <div class="plastic-number">4</div>
                    <img class="plastic-logo" src="/image/plaslogo4.png" alt="LDPE plastic symbol">
                    <h2 class="plastic-title">LDPE (Low-Density Polyethylene)</h2>
                    <p class="plastic-description">Used in squeezable bottles, shopping bags, and some food packaging. Flexible and transparent. Can be recycled into floor tiles, shipping envelopes, and new bags.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="plastic-card">
                    <div class="plastic-number">5</div>
                    <img class="plastic-logo" src="/image/plaslogo5.jpg" alt="PP plastic symbol">
                    <h2 class="plastic-title">PP (Polypropylene)</h2>
                    <p class="plastic-description">Found in food containers, bottle caps, and car parts. Heat-resistant and durable. Recyclable into battery cases, bins, and paint buckets.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="plastic-card">
                    <div class="plastic-number">6</div>
                    <img class="plastic-logo" src="/image/plaslogo6.webp" alt="PS plastic symbol">
                    <h2 class="plastic-title">PS (Polystyrene)</h2>
                    <p class="plastic-description">Used in disposable cutlery, packaging foam, and CD cases. Lightweight but environmentally problematic. Limited recycling options, best to avoid when possible.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="plastic-card">
                    <div class="plastic-number">7</div>
                    <img class="plastic-logo" src="/image/plaslogo7.webp" alt="Other plastics symbol">
                    <h2 class="plastic-title">Other Plastics</h2>
                    <p class="plastic-description">Includes mixed plastics and newer types like bioplastics. Properties vary widely. Recycling options depend on specific type and local facilities.</p>
                </div>
